at the size of those marks,

14:08.782 --> 14:12.116
we can get an idea of
the animal that it's battling.

14:13.185 --> 14:16.421
<i>[Harry] Hovland wonders
if the scientists' submersible</i>

14:16.423 --> 14:18.756
<i>has stumbled across
the gruesome remains</i>

14:18.758 --> 14:22.827
<i>of one of Planet Earth's
most epic battles,</i>

14:22.829 --> 14:27.832
<i>a face-off between an enormous
giant squid and a sperm whale.</i>

14:27.834 --> 14:29.934
<i>[Eric] Could that explain
what I'm seeing here?</i>

14:29.936 --> 14:33.304
A severed squid tentacle
of giant proportions.

14:35.941 --> 14:37.809
[waves crashing]

14:37.811 --> 14:39.344
<i>[Harry] Coming up...</i>

14:39.346 --> 14:41.379
<i>Is this tentacle still alive</i>

14:41.381 --> 14:43.314
<i>and poised to attack?</i>

14:43.316 --> 14:45.350
Imagine getting injected
with a chemical

14:45.352 --> 14:47.652
that dissolves you
from the inside out.

14:47.654 --> 14:49.454
It'd be a terrible way to go.

14:49.456 --> 14:53.191
<i>[Harry] And, a hairy,
square-eyed baby shocks doctors.</i>

14:53.193 --> 14:55.960
Are we looking at a science
experiment gone wrong?

14:55.962 --> 14:57.262
[static]

14:59.665 --> 15:00.665
[static]

15:03.636 --> 15:06.804
<i>[Harry] 65 miles
off the coast of Australia,</i>

15:06.806 --> 15:11.976
<i>a submersible encounters what
looks like a 150-foot-long tentacle.</i>

15:15.347 --> 15:18.182
<i>When marine biologist
Greg Szulgit zooms in,</i>

15:18.184 --> 15:23.221
<i>he notices this creepy cable has
other, smaller objects hanging off it.</i>

15:23.223 --> 15:24.822
<i>[Greg] I think that</i>

15:24.824 --> 15:27.425
tells us that this
is probably a siphonophore.

15:31.030 --> 15:32.230
<i>[Jayde] Forget about Jaws.</i>

15:32.232 --> 15:34.365
This giant is the new definition

15:34.367 --> 15:36.267
of horror from the deep.

15:37.036 --> 15:39.938
<i>[Harry] Most animals
grow as a single body.</i>

15:39.940 --> 15:43.207
<i>Siphonophores clone themselves
thousands of times</i>

15:43.209 --> 15:45.410
<i>to create a mega monster,</i>

15:45.412 --> 15:48.947
<i>and each clone
is given a singular purpose.</i>

15:48.949 --> 15:51.683
Some are digesting,
some are moving

15:51.685 --> 15:54.719
and it gives this large
sort of super organism

15:54.721 --> 15:56.454
that's absolutely huge.

15:57.489 --> 15:59.857
<i>[Harry] The clones are
all strung together</i>

15:59.859 --> 16:01.826
<i>into a chain of death,</i>

16:01.828 --> 16:04.963
<i>working as a team
to hunt and feed.</i>

16:04.965 --> 16:09.701
<i>And beneath its frilly fronds,
there is a deadly weapon.</i>

16:09.703 --> 16:13.004
Millions of individual
dangling fishing lines,

16:13.006 --> 16:14.839
with millions more hooks

16:14.841 --> 16:16.541
<i>all set out as bait.</i>

16:17.876 --> 16:21.212
These fishing lines are
bristling with stinging barbs

16:21.214 --> 16:24.148
<i>that are powerful enough to
punch through human skin</i>

16:24.150 --> 16:25.683
<i>and deliver a neurotoxin</i>

16:25.685 --> 16:28.519
that can cause
paralysis and death.

16:30.456 --> 16:33.057
<i>[Harry] The siphonophore
has evolved tricks</i>

16:33.059 --> 16:35.426
<i>to lure creatures
to their deaths.</i>

16:36.195 --> 16:38.896
<i>This one has bioluminescence,</i>

16:38.898 --> 16:42.333
<i>drawing light loving animals
towards their doom.</i>

16:42.968 --> 16:44.235
<i>[Eric] It's enormous,</i>

16:44.237 --> 16:47.305
<i>swirling, flat, sticky,</i>

16:47.307 --> 16:50.742
like a giant
seagoing spider web,

16:50.744 --> 16:53.011
except
the spider's built right in.

16:53.013 --> 16:57.148
Because the web is itself
the venomous predator.

16:58.283 --> 17:00.985
<i>[Harry] For any creature
caught in this deep sea web,</i>

17:00.987 --> 17:02.987
<i>it's not only death they face,</i>

17:02.989 --> 17:05.690
<i>it's an extremely gruesome end.</i>

17:05.692 --> 17:07.658
The way that creatures
like this feed

17:07.660 --> 17:09.193
is particularly disgusting.

17:11.764 --> 17:14.365
<i>Once they've paralyzed
and killed their prey,</i>

17:14.367 --> 17:16.467
<i>they inject
a dissolving chemical</i>

17:16.469 --> 17:20.104
<i>that turns the body of the
creature into a kind of soup,</i>

17:20.106 --> 17:22.106
and then they'll
suck that soup out

17:22.108 --> 17:23.975
and absorb all the nutrients.

17:25.444 --> 17:27.678
<i>Imagine getting
tangled up in one of these</i>

17:27.680 --> 17:28.913
<i>and then injected
with a chemical</i>

17:28.915 --> 17:31.315
that dissolves you
from the inside out.

17:31.317 --> 17:32.884
It'd be a terrible way to go.

17:32.886 --> 17:34.252
[waves lapping]

17:34.254 --> 17:36.120
<i>[Harry] In January 2019,</i>

17:36.122 --> 17:38.456
<i>over 1000 people were stung</i>

17:38.458 --> 17:43.094
<i>by an enormous swarm of
siphonophores off the Australian coast.</i>

17:44.196 --> 17:45.863
<i>[Jayde] I grew up,
as an Australian,</i>

17:45.865 --> 17:49.867
fearing getting tangled up
in one of those in the ocean.

17:49.869 --> 17:52.670
<i>[Harry] And siphonophores
much smaller than this one</i>

17:52.672 --> 17:54.505
<i>have killed humans.</i>

17:56.041 --> 17:57.642
<i>In 1987,</i>

17:57.644 --> 18:00.945
<i>a woman on the Florida coast
died in just minutes</i>

18:00.947 --> 18:05.183
<i>after being stung by a
siphonophore just 30-feet-long.</i>

18:06.051 --> 18:07.752
<i>The colossal creature
in the video</i>

18:07.754 --> 18:11.689
<i>may be 2000-feet-deep,
but there is chilling evidence</i>

18:11.691 --> 18:15.359
<i>siphonophores have evolved
clones into gasbags,</i>

18:15.361 --> 18:17.929
<i>enabling them
to rise to the surface</i>

18:17.931 --> 18:20.164
<i>where prey is more plentiful.</i>

18:20.166 --> 18:22.066
A giant siphonophore

18:22.068 --> 18:25.970
covered in stinging cells
and digestive juices

18:26.805 --> 18:29.674
redefines terror of the deep.

18:29.676 --> 18:32.176
<i>[Harry] And a sighting
of a massive siphonophore</i>

18:32.178 --> 18:35.379
<i>just 65 miles
off the coast of Australia</i>

18:35.381 --> 18:37.849
<i>should make any divers
think twice</i>

18:37.851 --> 18:39.183
<i>before taking the plunge.</i>

18:39.185 --> 18:41.686
<i>If it arrived on a beach,</i>

18:41.688 --> 18:45.456
<i>Australia's tourists
could be in peril.</i>

18:45.458 --> 18:47.692
If you happen
to get ensnared in this thing,

18:47.694 --> 18:50.962
you would die a death
of a thousand cuts.

18:50.964 --> 18:53.164
A little part of me,
sometimes thinks,

18:53.166 --> 18:57.301
"Maybe the mysteries of
the deep are best left alone

18:57.303 --> 19:01.405
when nightmare organisms like
this are right around the corner."

19:09.414 --> 19:11.015
<i>[Harry] Now,</i>

19:11.083 --> 19:12.416
<i>Nimodiya,</i>

19:12.418 --> 19:16.120
<i>a tiny village in Rajasthan,
northwest India.</i>

19:18.557 --> 19:21.392
<i>January 2020.</i>

19:21.394 --> 19:22.793
[percussion music]

19:22.795 --> 19:24.795
<i>[Harry] An infant is born.</i>

19:24.797 --> 19:26.864
<i>Villagers flock to the house,</i>

19:26.866 --> 19:29.100
<i>not to coo and congratulate,</i>

19:29.102 --> 19:31.202
<i>but to gasp in horror.</i>

19:34.339 --> 19:36.140
Oh. [gasps]

19:38.143 --> 19:40.144
Oh. Oh, my God.

19:43.081 --> 19:44.682
What is this creature?

19:45.450 --> 19:46.884
It looks human.

19:46.886 --> 19:49.086
<i>It's just incredibly hairy.</i>

19:50.022 --> 19:52.056
<i>[Harry] This is no monkey.</i>

19:53.025 --> 19:56.160
I'd say we're looking at
a very hairy baby.

19:58.197 --> 19:59.496
[static]

20:00.832 --> 20:04.702
<i>[Harry] Once, all human
babies were born this hairy.</i>

20:04.704 --> 20:06.771
<i>The five million hair follicles</i>

20:06.773 --> 20:11.776
<i>that cover our bodies sprouted
thick fur like a chimpanzee.</i>

20:11.778 --> 20:14.478
<i>But as we evolved
to hunt and run,</i>

20:14.480 --> 20:17.248
<i>cooler bodies became
more advantageous</i>

20:17.250 --> 20:19.383
<i>and our body hair thinned.</i>

20:20.219 --> 20:23.221
<i>But not everyone's DNA
got the memo.</i>

20:25.824 --> 20:27.992
<i>Jo-Jo the Dog-Faced Boy</i>

20:27.994 --> 20:30.294
<i>earned fame in the 19th century</i>

20:30.296 --> 20:33.898
<i>at P.T. Barnum's
The Greatest Show on Earth.</i>

20:33.900 --> 20:36.267
<i>He suffered
from excessive hair growth,</i>

20:36.269 --> 20:39.270
<i>a condition
now called hypertrichosis,</i>

20:39.272 --> 20:43.074
<i>but it was once known
as werewolf syndrome.</i>

20:44.142 --> 20:47.445
<i>And on stage,
Jojo was forced to growl,</i>

20:47.447 --> 20:50.414
<i>bear his teeth
and even chew raw meat</i>

20:50.416 --> 20:52.416
<i>to the cheers of the audience.</i>

20:53.352 --> 20:54.552
<i>Here in India,</i>

20:54.554 --> 20:57.755
<i>different looking children
are not treated as horrors,</i>

20:57.757 --> 20:59.323
<i>but as gods.</i>

20:59.325 --> 21:02.260
An awful lot of the
traditional religious figures

21:02.262 --> 21:04.495
are half-animal, half-human.

21:04.497 --> 21:06.530
Think about the god Ganesh,
for example,

21:06.532 --> 21:08.366
who is half-elephant.

21:08.800 --> 21:10.301
<i>[Harry] In 2015,</i>

21:10.303 --> 21:12.403
<i>people flocked
to worship a child</i>

21:12.405 --> 21:16.240
<i>born with a trunk-like
protrusion between her eyes.</i>

21:16.242 --> 21:19.310
<i>They called her Ganesha's wife.</i>

21:19.312 --> 21:22.179
Is it possible
that the villagers here,

21:22.181 --> 21:23.547
or the people that live here,

21:24.383 --> 21:27.118
<i>might see this creature
as some sort of God</i>

21:27.120 --> 21:29.186
<i>or some sort of higher being?</i>

21:32.090 --> 21:33.791
<i>[Harry] But when biologist
Carin Bondar</i>

21:33.793 --> 21:35.960
<i>searches through local records,</i>

21:35.962 --> 21:40.398
<i>she discovers this infant was
not born to a human mother.</i>

21:40.400 --> 21:42.900
This baby was born to a goat,

21:42.902 --> 21:44.702
but it does look like a human.

21:46.371 --> 21:48.205
[Ashanti]
<i>Its face is quite flat,</i>

21:48.207 --> 21:49.307
<i>it doesn't have a snout.</i>

21:49.309 --> 21:53.344
It has a chin
and quite a large forehead.

21:53.346 --> 21:57.648
<i>It should be a goat,
but it appears very human.</i>

21:58.684 --> 22:01.952
Why are animals being born
with human faces?

22:01.954 --> 22:03.020
[static]

22:06.491 --> 22:08.192
<i>[Harry] Coming up...</i>

22:08.194 --> 22:09.994
<i>Is this new kid on the block</i>

22:09.996 --> 22:12.063
<i>a human-goat hybrid?</i>

22:12.065 --> 22:13.898
I've seen enough movies to know

22:13.900 --> 22:17.468
that scientists
should not be splicing DNA.

22:17.470 --> 22:19.003
<i>[Harry] And,</i>

22:19.005 --> 22:22.139
<i>a suburb is shattered
by a trucking nightmare.</i>

22:22.141 --> 22:23.741
[explosion]

22:23.743 --> 22:25.443
They say,
"Don't shoot the messenger,"

22:25.445 --> 22:27.978
but in this case, it looks like
somebody tried to blow them up.

22:27.980 --> 22:30.081
[distant sirens]

22:30.083 --> 22:31.282
[static]

22:34.019 --> 22:35.353
[static]

22:38.023 --> 22:39.223
<i>[Harry] In an Indian village,</i>

22:39.225 --> 22:42.259
<i>a goat is born
with a human-looking face.</i>

22:43.095 --> 22:45.429
Could this be
a strange mutant crossbreed

22:45.431 --> 22:47.832
between a human and a goat?

22:47.834 --> 22:49.967
<i>[Harry] Visionary author
H.G. Wells</i>

22:49.969 --> 22:51.802
<i>wrote The Island of Dr. Moreau</i>

22:51.804 --> 22:53.938
<i>in 1896.</i>

22:53.940 --> 22:56.374
<i>A story about a crazed scientist</i>

22:56.376 --> 22:58.175
<i>creating animal-human hybrids.</i>

22:58.177 --> 22:59.577
[maniacal laughter]

23:01.480 --> 23:04.115
<i>[Harry] Shaena Montanari
investigates if someone</i>

23:04.117 --> 23:06.217
<i>is attempting
to do the same thing</i>

23:06.219 --> 23:08.452
<i>in this isolated Indian village.</i>

23:09.154 --> 23:11.455
For two species
to successfully mate,

23:11.457 --> 23:15.126
they ideally have to have the
same number of chromosomes.

23:15.827 --> 23:16.861
<i>For example,</i>

23:16.863 --> 23:19.697
<i>dogs and wolves
both have 78 chromosomes,</i>

23:19.699 --> 23:21.365
<i>which means
they can cross breed.</i>

23:21.367 --> 23:23.434
<i>[Harry] Crossbreeding
humans with other animals</i>

23:23.436 --> 23:25.236
<i>would be incredibly difficult,</i>

23:25.238 --> 23:26.604
<i>as even chimpanzees,</i>

23:26.606 --> 23:29.974
<i>with whom we share
99 percent of our DNA,</i>

23:29.976 --> 23:32.410
<i>have two more chromosomes
than we do,</i>

23:32.412 --> 23:35.579
<i>making offspring
almost impossible.</i>

23:36.782 --> 23:39.383
<i>Goats would be
even less of a match.</i>

23:39.385 --> 23:43.087
Goats have 60 chromosomes
and humans have 46.

23:43.089 --> 23:45.089
<i>The difference
is just way too big</i>

23:45.091 --> 23:48.092
<i>for goats and humans
to naturally hybridize.</i>

23:48.094 --> 23:49.693
[static]

23:51.963 --> 23:54.932
<i>[Harry] Biologist Carin Bondar
tries to discover</i>

23:54.934 --> 23:57.701
<i>how the goat ended up
looking so human.</i>

23:59.037 --> 24:00.805
The reason this goat
looks so strange

24:00.807 --> 24:03.808
is because
its eyes are forward-facing,

24:03.810 --> 24:05.643
kind of like
a predator's eyes would be.

24:07.813 --> 24:09.914
Goats are generally
prey animals,

24:09.916 --> 24:13.384
and so their eyes are on both
sides of their head to allow them

24:13.386 --> 24:15.853
<i>to view a lot of the ground
around them</i>

24:15.855 --> 24:18.522
<i>- to keep a lookout for predators.
- [bleating]</i>

24:18.524 --> 24:20.658
<i>[Harry] Bondar believes
the goat is suffering</i>

24:20.660 --> 24:22.593
<i>from a rare deformity.</i>

24:22.595 --> 24:26.931
<i>[Carin] Some mammals experience
a condition called holoprosencephaly,</i>

24:26.933 --> 24:31.268
where the two sides of the brain
fail to distinguish from each other,

24:31.270 --> 24:36.340
<i>and it results in the eyes
appearing far too close together.</i>

24:36.342 --> 24:38.442
[Harry]
<i>In extreme circumstances,</i>

24:38.444 --> 24:42.213
<i>this condition can result in a
single eye in the middle of the face,</i>

24:42.881 --> 24:44.415
<i>a Cyclops.</i>

24:44.950 --> 24:46.684
<i>Historians have speculated</i>

24:46.686 --> 24:49.353
<i>the legendary creature
of Greek mythology</i>

24:49.355 --> 24:52.656
<i>may have been inspired
by a similar deformity.</i>

24:53.792 --> 24:55.092
<i>But Ashanti Davis</i>

24:55.094 --> 24:57.261
<i>believes
the goat's freakish face</i>

24:57.263 --> 25:00.097
<i>is not just a random mutation.</i>

25:00.099 --> 25:01.765
So there are a number
of harmful substances

25:01.767 --> 25:03.100
called teratogens,

25:03.102 --> 25:07.805
and they actually impact the
development and growth of a fetus.

25:07.807 --> 25:11.308
[Harry] <i>Montanari studies the
area for possible teratogens,</i>

25:11.310 --> 25:14.478
<i>the toxic substances
that cause birth defects</i>

25:14.480 --> 25:19.116
<i>and discovers that India's
intensive farming could be to blame.</i>

25:19.118 --> 25:21.252
India has
a lot of mouths to feed.

25:23.722 --> 25:26.924
<i>It's the second most
populous country after China,</i>

25:26.926 --> 25:29.426
<i>and that puts
a lot of pressure on farming.</i>

25:29.428 --> 25:31.128
[distant rumble of machinery]

25:31.130 --> 25:34.331
<i>[Shaena] As a result, farmers
are overfertilizing their fields</i>

25:34.333 --> 25:37.101
to get maximum crop yields.

25:37.103 --> 25:40.304
<i>[Harry] India spreads 50
million tons of chemical fertilizer</i>

25:40.306 --> 25:42.439
<i>on its crops each year.</i>

25:42.441 --> 25:45.543
The excess nitrogen
washes into waterways

25:45.545 --> 25:48.979
and is consumed
by local communities.

25:48.981 --> 25:51.148
<i>[Harry] Nitrogen
and nitrate chemicals</i>

25:51.150 --> 25:53.150
<i>cause abnormal
fetal development,</i>

25:53.152 --> 25:54.752
<i>and in some areas,</i>

25:54.754 --> 25:59.924
<i>they're seeping into the water supply
in quantities far beyond safe limits.</i>

25:59.926 --> 26:02.359
It's likely
that excess nitrogen levels

26:02.361 --> 26:04.562
<i>caused the birth defect
in the goat.</i>

26:04.564 --> 26:07.197
<i>But whatever
the goat is exposed to,</i>

26:07.199 --> 26:09.133
so are the people.

26:09.135 --> 26:12.036
In order to try to feed
its population better,

26:12.038 --> 26:15.005
India could actually
be poisoning them as well.

26:15.007 --> 26:18.342
- [bell chimes] <i>- [Harry] The
gruesome-faced goat is cared for</i>

26:18.344 --> 26:22.846
<i>and worshiped as an avatar of
the Hindu Gods by the local villagers.</i>

26:22.848 --> 26:24.315
<i>But rather than a God,</i>

26:24.317 --> 26:27.318
<i>it may instead
be a prophet of doom,</i>

26:27.320 --> 26:29.820
<i>signifying
the potential devastation</i>

26:29.822 --> 26:33.657
<i>chemical fertilizers
can inflict on the young.</i>

26:33.659 --> 26:36.093
<i>[Ashanti] Harmful teratogens
are closer to home</i>

26:36.095 --> 26:37.561
than we would really like.

26:37.563 --> 26:42.333
The implications for the next
generations are catastrophic.

26:46.871 --> 26:48.939
<i>[Harry] Now,</i>

26:48.941 --> 26:50.574
<i>Kansas City, Missouri.</i>

26:55.113 --> 26:57.982
<i>January 23, 2019.</i>

26:59.451 --> 27:01.218
[snow crunching]

27:01.220 --> 27:02.753
<i>[Harry] In a quiet suburb,</i>

27:02.755 --> 27:07.024
<i>a doorbell camera films
the snowbound street outside.</i>

27:09.260 --> 27:12.062
So it's a peaceful,
pleasant neighborhood.

27:14.532 --> 27:15.966
And all of a sudden, boom.

27:15.968 --> 27:18.268
[explosion]

27:18.270 --> 27:20.170
There's an explosion

27:20.172 --> 27:22.239
right in the middle
of the street.

27:22.241 --> 27:25.075
<i>[Harry] Just yards
from family homes,</i>

27:25.077 --> 27:28.078
<i>a vehicle mysteriously
bursts into flames.</i>

27:28.080 --> 27:29.246
[explosion]

27:29.248 --> 27:32.449
Whoa, this is wild.

27:32.451 --> 27:35.486
It's terrifying how quickly
this car just goes up.

27:35.488 --> 27:37.821
It went from nothing
to a fireball.

27:37.823 --> 27:39.657
[distant flames billowing]

27:39.659 --> 27:42.192
<i>[Harry] Then the blazing
vehicle lurches backwards</i>

27:42.194 --> 27:45.295
<i>and races down the hill
towards the houses.</i>

27:45.297 --> 27:46.897
[distant clattering]

27:46.899 --> 27:50.334
It's like a rolling fireball
moving down the street.

27:50.336 --> 27:52.636
- [distant clattering]
- [distant flames billowing]

27:54.706 --> 27:57.841
The situation is quickly
getting out of control.

27:57.843 --> 28:00.010
- [distant clattering]
- [distant xpl]

28:03.181 --> 28:05.683
<i>[Harry] This isn't
any ordinary vehicle.</i>

28:06.284 --> 28:08.152
<i>Historian Ashanti Davis</i>

28:08.154 --> 28:10.954
<i>analyses the dimensions
of the vehicle</i>

28:10.956 --> 28:13.090
<i>and discovers
it's a type of truck</i>

28:13.092 --> 28:16.860
<i>seen on every street in America.</i>

28:16.862 --> 28:19.863
The shape and size
of this is quite familiar.

28:19.865 --> 28:24.234
It has a very boxy shape
and a very distinct nose.

28:24.236 --> 28:27.304
This is a U.S. Postal Service
mail truck.

28:30.341 --> 28:33.043
<i>[Harry] Former CIA operative
Tracy Walder</i>

28:33.045 --> 28:35.379
<i>believes the raging inferno
could be caused</i>

28:35.381 --> 28:39.817
<i>by a type of package you
definitely don't want to receive.</i>

28:39.819 --> 28:42.219
All sorts of suspicious things
get sent in the mail,

28:42.221 --> 28:43.554
but some of them are deadly.

28:45.857 --> 28:49.126
<i>The initial blast is fast.</i>

28:49.128 --> 28:53.897
This is indicative of an
incendiary device, or a bomb.

28:53.899 --> 28:56.233
<i>[Harry] Mail bombs have been
sent through the American mail</i>

28:56.235 --> 28:58.102
<i>since 1919,</i>

28:58.104 --> 29:02.005
<i>when anarchists mailed
36 explosive devices</i>

29:02.007 --> 29:04.908
<i>to politicians
around the country.</i>

29:04.910 --> 29:08.378
<i>But the threat of death
by mail hasn't diminished.</i>

29:08.380 --> 29:12.249
<i>In 2018,
a 23-year-old college dropout,</i>

29:12.251 --> 29:16.954
<i>Mark Condit, wages a war
of terror on Austin, Texas.</i>

29:16.956 --> 29:19.356
<i>His five homemade
package bombs kill two</i>

29:19.358 --> 29:21.492
<i>and injure five more
over three weeks.</i>

29:23.061 --> 29:27.197
<i>He's finally identified
by a store CCTV camera.</i>

29:27.199 --> 29:30.234
<i>Police pursue him
along Interstate 35,</i>

29:30.902 --> 29:32.269
<i>but when he's pulled over,</i>

29:32.271 --> 29:35.639
<i>Condit blows himself up
instead of being captured.</i>

29:36.341 --> 29:37.875
<i>[Brian] Just imagine</i>

29:37.877 --> 29:41.011
if the item
that caused this explosion

29:41.013 --> 29:43.580
actually was mailed
through your door.

29:43.582 --> 29:45.415
[explosion]

29:47.252 --> 29:50.821
<i>[Harry] The threat of death
by mail is considered so great,</i>

29:50.823 --> 29:54.391
<i>the U.S. Postal Service
employs a full time team</i>

29:54.393 --> 29:56.927
<i>to monitor packages
for explosives</i>

29:56.929 --> 29:58.796
<i>and biochemical weapons.</i>

29:58.798 --> 30:00.864
Weird-shaped items,

30:00.866 --> 30:04.001
<i>no return addresses,
even misspelled names</i>

30:04.003 --> 30:06.236
<i>are all red flags.</i>

30:06.238 --> 30:09.706
Could this be a letter bomb that has
exploded before reaching its target?

30:16.314 --> 30:17.915
<i>[Harry] Coming up...</i>

30:17.917 --> 30:22.052
<i>Reports of mystery fires
in America's mail vans.</i>

30:22.054 --> 30:24.321
<i>[Nick] They've occurred
in the battery compartment,</i>

30:24.323 --> 30:26.356
in the fuel pump,
in the dashboard.

30:27.192 --> 30:28.959
<i>[Harry] And, a pilot films</i>

30:28.961 --> 30:31.295
<i>a weird object from his cockpit.</i>

30:31.297 --> 30:34.898
This is what I would consider
a genuine UFO.

30:34.900 --> 30:36.867
<i>There is a flying object here,</i>

30:36.869 --> 30:39.203
<i>and I have no idea what it is.</i>

30:47.178 --> 30:49.680
<i>[Harry] A mail truck
spontaneously combusts</i>

30:49.682 --> 30:51.949
<i>on a Kansas City street.</i>

30:53.117 --> 30:54.351
[keyboard clicking]

30:54.353 --> 30:56.486
<i>[Harry] Data scientist
Liberty Vittert</i>

30:56.488 --> 31:00.023
<i>isolates and analyzes
the audio from the footage</i>

31:00.025 --> 31:03.160
<i>and notices an unusual noise.</i>

31:03.162 --> 31:06.029
Just before the explosion,
you can hear a whining sound.

31:06.031 --> 31:07.564
[whining sound]

31:09.100 --> 31:11.401
I think
that's the engine revving

31:11.403 --> 31:16.139
or the wheels spinning as the van
struggles to get up the snowy street.

31:16.141 --> 31:18.675
[explosion]

31:18.677 --> 31:22.112
Could this explosion be
attributed to the van itself?

31:22.114 --> 31:25.649
So something wrong with
the design or manufacture.

31:29.387 --> 31:31.421
<i>[Harry] Engineer
Nick Householder discovers</i>

31:31.423 --> 31:35.959
<i>that the aging fleet
of USPS trucks is obsolete.</i>

31:37.128 --> 31:40.030
<i>[Nick] The Long-Life Vehicle
known as the LLV,</i>

31:40.032 --> 31:42.332
<i>was selected in 1987</i>

31:42.334 --> 31:45.502
after a 24,000 mile
durability test.

31:45.770 --> 31:47.304
[engine buzzing]

31:47.372 --> 31:51.375
<i>[Harry] These vans help to deliver
48 percent of the world's mail,</i>

31:51.377 --> 31:57.414
<i>over 170 million items of
first class mail alone each day.</i>

31:57.416 --> 32:02.019
<i>There are over 140,000 LLVs
still in service,</i>

32:02.021 --> 32:04.821
<i>and some are showing their age.</i>

32:04.823 --> 32:07.024
<i>Since 2017,</i>

32:07.026 --> 32:10.594
<i>reports claim over 100 mail
trucks have caught on fire</i>

32:10.596 --> 32:13.196
<i>without being involved
in a crash.</i>

32:13.198 --> 32:16.867
These fires have occurred in
hot climates and in cold climates.

32:16.869 --> 32:18.969
They've occurred in
the battery compartment,

32:18.971 --> 32:21.605
<i>in the fuel pump,
in the dashboard.</i>

32:22.874 --> 32:26.376
<i>[Harry] This fire was likely
caused by tire shrapnel</i>

32:26.378 --> 32:30.280
<i>hitting the engine as the driver
tried to accelerate up the snowy hill.</i>

32:30.282 --> 32:31.815
[siren wailing]

32:31.817 --> 32:33.917
<i>[Harry] The mailman
escapes unharmed.</i>

32:33.919 --> 32:36.887
<i>When firefighters arrive
at the scene in Kansas City,</i>

32:36.889 --> 32:41.024
<i>all they can do is keep the
fire away from nearby buildings.</i>

32:41.026 --> 32:42.326
<i>The 30-year-old truck,</i>

32:42.328 --> 32:46.029
<i>and the mail it's carrying,
is destroyed.</i>

32:46.031 --> 32:49.566
This gives a whole new meaning
to special delivery.

32:57.475 --> 32:58.942
- [wind blowing]
<i>- [Harry] Now,</i>

32:58.944 --> 33:01.712
<i>the sky above
Colombia, South America.</i>

33:04.415 --> 33:07.017
<i>January 1st, 2020.</i>

33:07.652 --> 33:09.353
[jet engine whirring]

33:12.924 --> 33:15.292
<i>[Harry] Pilot
Cesar Murillo Perez,</i>

33:15.294 --> 33:19.830
<i>flying an A320
with a capacity of 180 people,</i>

33:19.832 --> 33:23.533
<i>spies a fast moving object
approaching his aircraft.</i>

33:30.808 --> 33:32.175
<i>[Amy] Imagine sitting in a plane</i>

33:32.177 --> 33:33.910
<i>and seeing this weird object</i>

33:33.912 --> 33:36.613
flying towards you
at a rapid speed.

33:38.049 --> 33:40.951
It looked like
a metallic golf ball

33:40.953 --> 33:42.986
flying through the clouds.

33:44.956 --> 33:50.360
<i>[Harry] It has no propellers,
no exhaust, no wings, no tail.</i>

33:50.362 --> 33:53.430
That thing looks like it
shouldn't even be able to fly,

33:53.432 --> 33:57.200
but there it is, speeding
along at about 30,000 feet.

33:57.202 --> 33:59.269
Passenger planes
are supposed to fly

33:59.271 --> 34:01.438
in carefully
controlled corridors.

34:01.440 --> 34:04.408
<i>Seeing an object like this
outside your window</i>

34:04.410 --> 34:06.309
<i>has got to be shocking.</i>

34:09.380 --> 34:12.015
<i>[Harry] Perez checks
his cockpit radar,</i>

34:12.017 --> 34:15.452
<i>but what he sees
just deepens the mystery.</i>

34:16.421 --> 34:18.055
<i>[George] It doesn't show up.</i>

34:18.057 --> 34:21.992
It's just a thing
that they go flying past.

34:23.494 --> 34:26.897
<i>This is what I would consider
a genuine UFO.</i>

34:26.899 --> 34:30.700
There is a flying object here
and I have no idea what it is.

34:35.006 --> 34:36.873
[computer mouse clicking]

34:36.875 --> 34:39.342
<i>[Harry] Image analyst
Conor McCourt runs the footage</i>

34:39.344 --> 34:42.179
<i>through enhancement software.</i>

34:42.181 --> 34:46.883
What I'm doing here is zooming in
and having a good look at this object.

34:46.885 --> 34:50.720
We have one, two,
three and four corners.

34:50.722 --> 34:51.888
<i>It's cube like,</i>

34:51.989 --> 34:55.292
<i>it has reflective properties
that could be metallic.</i>

34:56.627 --> 34:59.262
<i>They're not seeing
wings or other motors</i>

34:59.264 --> 35:01.898
or any kind of
mechanical devices

35:01.900 --> 35:04.334
that would propel this
through the air.

35:04.336 --> 35:07.871
<i>[Harry] And this
is no inflatable balloon.</i>

35:07.873 --> 35:10.006
<i>[Nick] I don't think
this is a balloon</i>

35:10.008 --> 35:13.176
because they're usually designed
to go to much higher altitudes.

35:13.178 --> 35:15.011
<i>They're more of a teardrop shape</i>

35:15.013 --> 35:18.048
<i>as they're pulling a cargo
up into the atmosphere.</i>

35:19.117 --> 35:23.420
There's nothing that indicates
that this object should fly.

35:23.422 --> 35:26.456
<i>It should plummet
like a stone to the Earth.</i>

35:30.394 --> 35:31.327
<i>[Harry] Coming up...</i>

35:31.395 --> 35:33.730
<i>Is this craft
linked to a scientist</i>

35:33.732 --> 35:35.899
<i>who mysteriously disappeared?</i>

35:35.901 --> 35:40.971
<i>[Tim] So she's claiming she
could make a gravity force field,</i>

35:40.973 --> 35:45.775
something that the American
government wanted to keep as a secret.

35:45.777 --> 35:49.246
- [distorted radio static]
- [pilot speaking]

35:56.921 --> 36:00.090
<i>[Harry] A mysterious craft
is spotted by an airline pilot</i>

36:00.092 --> 36:03.660
<i>30,000 feet
above the skies of Colombia.</i>

36:06.464 --> 36:10.267
<i>Historian Craig Gottlieb finds
more reports of flying objects</i>

36:10.269 --> 36:12.002
<i>that like this spinning cube</i>

36:12.004 --> 36:15.305
<i>seem to defy
the physics of flight.</i>

36:15.307 --> 36:18.975
In 2017, journalists
published leaked footage

36:18.977 --> 36:21.344
captured by Navy pilots

36:21.346 --> 36:23.380
of unidentified
aerial phenomena.

36:24.182 --> 36:25.749
<i>[Harry] In 2004,</i>

36:25.751 --> 36:27.717
<i>the USS Nimitz carrier group</i>

36:27.719 --> 36:30.020
<i>patrolling the waters
off San Diego,</i>

36:30.022 --> 36:34.357
<i>spots an unidentified object
on its radar.</i>

36:34.359 --> 36:38.828
<i>FA 18 super hornets
are scrambled to investigate</i>

36:38.830 --> 36:41.965
<i>and what they find
is mind boggling.</i>

36:41.967 --> 36:45.302
The pilot reports seeing
like a Tic Tac shaped craft

36:45.304 --> 36:47.971
<i>close to the surface
of the water.</i>

36:47.973 --> 36:50.807
<i>- [pilot] IHR2, it's following behind, over.
- [beeping]</i>

36:50.809 --> 36:52.209
<i>[Paco] Hold it up,
It's just hanging there</i>

36:52.211 --> 36:55.045
with no visible means
of lift or thrust.

36:55.047 --> 36:56.346
[beeping]

36:56.348 --> 36:59.916
<i>[Paco] If it was a helicopter
or an aero type V style jet,</i>

36:59.918 --> 37:03.653
there would just be
a massive plume of hot gases

37:03.655 --> 37:04.921
that would be flowing from it.

37:04.923 --> 37:09.125
<i>None of that
occurs on this footage.</i>

37:09.127 --> 37:13.964
<i>[Harry] And it pulls maneuvers which
would tear a normal airplane apart.</i>

37:13.966 --> 37:15.632
And suddenly
it takes off vertically.

37:15.634 --> 37:17.200
[indistinct radio chatter]

37:17.202 --> 37:19.836
<i>- [Craig] Accelerates out.
- [indistinct radio chatter]</i>

37:19.838 --> 37:21.204
<i>[Paco] Very quickly.
You know, it goes</i>

37:21.206 --> 37:22.672
from zero to whatever,

37:22.674 --> 37:23.974
800 miles an hour or more,

37:23.976 --> 37:26.376
1000 an hour almost instantly.

37:27.011 --> 37:28.979
<i>That G Force would be,</i>

37:28.981 --> 37:31.281
<i>I think fatal to any human.</i>

37:31.283 --> 37:32.449
[beeping]

37:33.818 --> 37:35.685
<i>[Harry] In 2015,</i>

37:35.687 --> 37:38.188
<i>a similar craft
is spotted again,</i>

37:38.190 --> 37:40.690
<i>this time,
off the east coast of America.</i>

37:41.792 --> 37:43.793
<i>[Tim] What's
really interesting is</i>

37:43.795 --> 37:45.495
<i>you can hear the pilots' voice</i>

37:45.497 --> 37:47.530
and they're really surprised.

37:48.032 --> 37:50.300
[pilot 1 speaking]

37:54.438 --> 37:55.805
- [laughter]
- [indistinct radio chatter]

37:55.807 --> 37:56.940
[pilot 2 speaking]

37:56.942 --> 37:58.708
<i>[man over radio] Yeah,
it's just strafing.</i>

37:59.410 --> 38:01.378
[pilot 1 speaking]

38:06.217 --> 38:09.185
<i>[Harry] The Pentagon confirms
the footage is genuine,</i>

38:09.187 --> 38:13.123
<i>but has no explanation
for what the object could be.</i>

38:13.125 --> 38:16.726
And if governments are
releasing genuine footage of UFOs

38:16.728 --> 38:18.862
and they themselves
don't know what it is,

38:18.864 --> 38:21.298
then that's something probably
we should worry about.

38:21.300 --> 38:25.402
<i>[Harry] The United States
now acknowledges that UFOs</i>

38:25.404 --> 38:28.338
<i>like the one in the footage
shot by the Colombian pilot,</i>

38:28.340 --> 38:29.839
<i>exist,</i>

38:29.841 --> 38:32.809
<i>but the notion that
they could be alien spacecraft</i>

38:32.811 --> 38:37.213
<i>could be a smokescreen
perpetuated by the military.</i>

38:37.215 --> 38:40.650
So some are claiming
that Pentagon is creating

38:40.652 --> 38:43.053
this quote "UFO hype"

38:43.120 --> 38:45.221
for a cover story

38:45.223 --> 38:50.894
<i>because they don't want people
knowing about their special projects.</i>

38:50.896 --> 38:55.665
<i>[Harry] Special projects that could
change life on Earth as we know it.</i>

38:55.667 --> 38:57.934
For years now,
there have been theories about

38:57.936 --> 39:01.237
<i>the development
of anti-gravity technology.</i>

39:01.239 --> 39:03.306
<i>[Harry] Gravity
is an invisible force</i>

39:03.308 --> 39:07.277
<i>that pulls smaller objects
towards larger ones.</i>

39:07.279 --> 39:10.380
<i>It's what holds the planets
in orbit around the Sun,</i>

39:10.382 --> 39:11.414
<i>and on Earth,</i>

39:11.416 --> 39:14.184
<i>it keeps objects on the ground.</i>

39:14.186 --> 39:16.519
<i>Planes and birds
can overcome the force</i>

39:16.521 --> 39:18.388
<i>with lift and thrust.</i>

39:18.889 --> 39:20.323
<i>But ultimately,</i>

39:20.325 --> 39:23.293
<i>what goes up must come down.</i>

39:24.095 --> 39:25.462
<i>But what if it didn't?</i>

39:25.464 --> 39:27.997
<i>Could scientists discover a way</i>

39:27.999 --> 39:31.267
<i>to shield something
from the force of gravity?</i>

39:31.269 --> 39:34.537
<i>In other words,
an anti-gravity device?</i>

39:34.939 --> 39:36.506
It sounds far-fetched,

39:36.841 --> 39:39.876
but the U.S. military has been seeking
to harness anti-gravity technology

39:39.878 --> 39:42.112
for over 70 years.

39:42.114 --> 39:45.949
The implications of anti-gravity
technology are enormous.

39:46.917 --> 39:49.452
<i>[Harry] Whole cities
could potentially be suspended</i>

39:49.454 --> 39:52.789
<i>in the sky
or deep under the sea.</i>

39:52.791 --> 39:54.357
<i>The design
and layout of buildings</i>

39:54.359 --> 39:57.093
<i>would alter
in unimaginable ways.</i>

39:57.095 --> 40:00.296
I mean, we're talking
science fiction stuff here.

40:01.098 --> 40:02.732
<i>[Harry] But
spaceflight historian</i>

40:02.734 --> 40:05.735
<i>Amy Shira Teitel
has uncovered evidence</i>

40:05.737 --> 40:08.538
<i>that the theoretical world
of anti-gravity</i>

40:08.540 --> 40:11.941
<i>is secretly starting
to move into practice.</i>

40:11.943 --> 40:12.942
<i>[Amy] In the 1990s,</i>

40:12.944 --> 40:15.578
physicist Ning Li releases work,

40:15.580 --> 40:20.884
saying that she's figured out
how to shield the effects of gravity.

40:20.886 --> 40:23.953
<i>[Harry] Dr. Ning Li's theory
declared that if a magnetic field</i>

40:23.955 --> 40:26.489
<i>was applied
to superconductive ions</i>

40:26.491 --> 40:28.758
<i>trapped in a lattice structure,</i>

40:28.760 --> 40:31.060
<i>they would begin to rapidly spin</i>

40:31.062 --> 40:33.363
<i>and create
a gravitational field,</i>

40:33.365 --> 40:36.766
<i>counteracting
Earth's gravitational pull.</i>

40:36.768 --> 40:37.767
And so she's claiming

40:37.769 --> 40:41.137
she can make
a gravity force field.

40:44.508 --> 40:47.544
[Harry] <i>Anti-Gravity technology
would allow craft to move</i>

40:47.546 --> 40:50.413
<i>in previously impossible ways.</i>

40:52.183 --> 40:54.217
<i>They might look
like the object filmed</i>

40:54.219 --> 40:56.453
<i>by the pilot
flying over Colombia.</i>

40:58.355 --> 41:00.089
<i>In 2001,</i>

41:00.091 --> 41:03.660
<i>Dr. Li receives a half a million
dollars from the Pentagon</i>

41:03.662 --> 41:05.962
<i>to further her research.</i>

41:05.964 --> 41:07.864
<i>And in 2003,</i>

41:07.866 --> 41:10.099
<i>she announces a breakthrough.</i>

41:10.835 --> 41:13.169
She had sent an email
to her colleague

41:13.171 --> 41:19.809
saying she had demonstrated a
large amount of anti-gravity phenomena

41:19.811 --> 41:21.377
and she was excited about it.

41:23.113 --> 41:25.448
<i>So had Ning Li
discovered something</i>

41:25.450 --> 41:29.686
<i>that the American government
wanted to keep as a secret?</i>

41:32.289 --> 41:33.423
<i>[Antonio] Is that
what we're seeing here</i>

41:33.425 --> 41:36.259
is some type of
experimental aircraft?

41:36.261 --> 41:38.361
<i>[Harry] If the U.S. government
has knowledge</i>

41:38.363 --> 41:40.230
<i>of these gravity defying craft</i>

41:40.232 --> 41:42.699
<i>flying above the skies
of the Americas...</i>

41:42.701 --> 41:44.634
[indistinct radio chatter]

41:46.704 --> 41:48.571
[Harry]
<i>they're not admitting it.</i>

41:51.242 --> 41:53.042
<i>[Tim] This footage is proof</i>

41:53.044 --> 41:55.678
that there's a whole lot more
going on in the skies

41:55.680 --> 41:57.347
that we don't know about.
